Project #2¶

For my exploratory data analysis I have chosen to analyze something that has always fascinated me. Going into this project I initially had a few different subjects on my mind. Initially, I had it in my head that I would explore some data on weather and climate, possibly to see if the conclusions made regarding climate change were as serious as the news claimed. However, with further though I have decided that I would like to delve into some of the infectios diseases that once plagued the world, amassing hundreds of thousands of cases as the developing world was taking shape in the 19th and 20th centuries as medicine began to evolve into what we have today.

Poliomyelitis, more commonly known as polio virus, was feared from parents across the globe as it occured primarily in children of ages 5 or under. It would appear initially as a cold, with fever, fatigue, and headache as the initial symptoms. However, it could lead to permanent paralysis. Particularly, paralysis in the lower extremities and possibly death if the paralysis takes form in the neck. Famously, President Franklin Delanor Roosevelt suffered greatly from the disease beginning at age 39, although this is quite uncommon.

In my analysis, there are some things that I would like to know about the disease.

  1. How rampant was the disease across the globe?
  2. What country suffered the greatest from the disease?
  3. What were some trends throughout the development of the disease (plot the year)?
  4. Where was Polio the most dominant in the 1980s?
  5. Where does the disease still exist in the world?
  6. What were some areas that have removed the threat of polio?
  7. How did Covid-19 impact the number of cases? How does the invention of the vaccine contribute to the number of cases?
  8. Why did Covid-19 have such an affect on the number of paralytic poliomyelitis cases?

Data Gathering¶

In looking for an open source database I have found 2 databases that I will analyze throughout the course of this project. In the first one I have the total reported polio cases in all of the countries across the world from the years 1980-2020. In my search this was the furthest back I could find with a reliable dataset, as I obtained the data from the CDC, by the link: https://ourworldindata.org/polio#all-charts. It can be downloaded in the 2nd chart. I will upload the csv file as a data frame below.

The code above shows that 154 countries have reported cases and over 4.8 million countries have reported cases in the last 40 years. This means that polio has presented itself as a widespread disease across the last 40 years.

Answer to Question 5¶

Performing an analysis on the lists generated, it is interesting to note that all of the countries that continue to have cases of paralytic poliomyelitis are occuring in third world or developing countries, as all of the developed world has eradicated the disease. Many people know that polio has had a vaccine created in the United States of America, and it is typical for children to recieve multiple shots of the live vaccine to fight against further infection.

Question 6, What countries have removed the threat of polio?¶

To answer this, I will generate the difference between the first 5 years of data and the final five years of data to see which countries have to conclude which countries have reduced the number of cases the most.

I will generate the difference column using a simple subtraction between the two columns I generated titled "1980-1984" and "2016-2020".

In [192]:
df['difference_firstlast5'] = df['2016-2020']-df['1980-1984']
most_removed = df.sort_values('difference_firstlast5',ascending = True)[0:5]
most_removed[['Country','difference_firstlast5']]

Answer to Question 6¶

Over the past 40 years, India has decreased their cases of polio the most, having 900,000 less cases in 2016-2020 than in 1980-1984 at the beginning of the dataset.

Question 7, How did Covid-19 impact the number of cases on the world?¶

On first thought, the sheltering of individuals during the epidemic would lead me to think that the number of cases would likely be lower than the year before. However, before I jump to any conclusion I will first take a glance at the cases before and during the year that Covid-19 tolk hold of the world.

I will first use the .sum() function to calculate the difference in the total number of cases between 2020 and 2019.

In [194]:
"The sum of the cases in 2020 was " + str(df['2020'].sum() - df['2019'].sum()) + " more than that of 2019."
Out[194]:
'The sum of the cases in 2020 was 2439.0 more than that of 2019.'

Now I will calculate the percentage increase of cases during 2020 over 2019 using the basic formula.

In [195]:
"This is signifigant as the total number of cases in 2019 was " + str(df['2019'].sum()) + " meaning the number of cases in 2020 was " + str(df['2020'].sum()) + ", which is a " + str(((df['2020'].sum())/(df['2019'].sum()))*100) + "% increase in cases during covid over the previous year."
Out[195]:
'This is signifigant as the total number of cases in 2019 was 1305.0 meaning the number of cases in 2020 was 3744.0, which is a 286.8965517241379% increase in cases during covid over the previous year.'

Answer to Question 7¶

It is obvious that Covid-19 had an affect on the number of polio cases across the world, with a 286% increase in cases. However, next I will explore why the polio virus was able to spread so much despite the intense effort at social isolazation in so many countries.

Answer to Question 8¶

The invention of the vaccine seems to have made a signifigant impact to the number of cases of polio. Looking at the sum variable that we calculated earlier and the plot of the vaccine data, we can see that the total number of cases has an inverse relationship with the percentage of the population who recieved the vaccine.
